text_x: So it's been about a month I have been in the nft space. I haven't had a great experience so far to be honest so I am taking a step back to think about if I want to put more effort and money into it. I have unlisted and burned most of my works but there are still some available.
text_y: @TheoChron NFT's are just a tool. Some artists want to use it as a way to show provenance of their work. Others want to use the token itself as some sort of art. Others just see it as a way to sell their digital work in a decentralized way that gives the middle finger to legacy systems.

text_x: So it's been about a month I have been in the nft space. I haven't had a great experience so far to be honest so I am taking a step back to think about if I want to put more effort and money into it. I have unlisted and burned most of my works but there are still some available.
text_y: @TheoChron a more compelling argument would be that high end commerce has hijacked / seduced a corner of the avant garde as a form of conceptual populism and this cultural force leads directly into NFT market as illustrational populism. KAWS being the bridge between the two.

@web An NFT is an ETH smart contract that requires transactional fees in ETH called gas fees.

As the number of ETH transactions increases, it causes the gas prices to go up, this in turn incentives the people to buy more ETH which increases the price of Ether.
